Welcome

With the Womenâs EURO 2025 final approaching this weekend, weâll build a reproducible pipeline to predict Englandâs chance of winning the final against Spain, using information of their performance over the past year.

You will:

  • Simulate the likely outcome of the final.
  • Use here for file paths and renv to lock package versions.

  • Make the project fully reproducible and shareable.

Installing Git

  • macOS
  • Windows

Git is often pre-installed on macOS. You can check by typing in the Terminal:

If itâs not installed, run:

You can optionally install GitHub Desktop, a graphical interface for Git and GitHub, by following the instructions here.

You can download Git for Windows from https://git-scm.com. Run the installer and accept default options, in particular:

âUse Git from the command line and also from 3rd-party softwareâ

You can optionally install GitHub Desktop, a graphical interface for Git and GitHub, by following the instructions here.

ð Authentication

To push and pull from GitHub, you need to authenticate. There are two options:

  • GitHub Desktop
  • SSH keys
  • This is a good place to start if youâre new to Git.
  • When you first log in via GitHub Desktop, it stores a token securely.
  • You can clone, commit, push, and pull without dealing with passwords or keys.

  • Recommended for longer-term use.
  • Requires access to a command line.

  1. Generate a key (if you donât have one):

    ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"

  2. Copy the key to your clipboard

    # macOS
pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

# Windows using Git Bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub | clip

  3. Add it to GitHub:

  • Go to GitHub â Settings â SSH and GPG keys.
  • Click âNew SSH keyâ and paste your generated key.

  1. Tell Git to use the key:

    git remote set-url origin git@github.com:username/repo.git

1 Create a project in RStudio

  1. Create a new RStudio Project:

    File > New Project > New Directory

  2. Give it an appropriate name (e.g., euros-prediction).

2 Download the scripts and datasets

Click the links below to download the required scripts and dataset:

  • 02-analysis.R
  • 03-plot.R

3 Initialise renv and install the required packages

In the console, type:

1install.packages("renv")
2renv::init()
3renv::install()
4renv::snapshot()
1
Install the renv package. You only need to do this onceânot for each project.
2
Initialise renv for the current project.
3
Install packages required for this project.
4
Save the current state into renv.lock.

Open the renv.lock lockfile to understand its contents.

4 Run the three scripts

  • Import and clean data
  • Predict the next match
  • Visualise

Run 01_clean.R in RStudio. This script:

  1. Imports the fixtures.csv dataset from the data/raw folder.
  2. Performs data cleaning, adding venue, Elo ratings, rest days, and form.
  3. Saves a cleaned dataset to data/clean/fixtures.rds.

Run 02_analysis.R in RStudio. This script:

  1. Fits two Poisson regression models to predict:
    • Englandâs goals
    • Opponentâs goals
  2. Simulates 1000 match results
  3. Saved the probabilities to outputs/results.rds

Run 03_plot.R in RStudio. This script:

  1. Loads the saved probabilities (outputs/results.rds).
  2. Creates a bar chart of predicted win/draw/loss.
  3. Saves the figure to outputs/prediction_plot.png.

5 Putting it all together

Create a new script run.R at the project root with the contents:

library(here)
source(here("scripts", "01-clean.R"))
source(here("scripts", "02-analysis.R"))
source(here("scripts", "03-plot.R"))

This script uses source to run the three scripts sequentially, avoiding the need to run in separately.

Run the run.R script either by clicking Run or at the console by typing:

source("run.R")

6 Initialise the Git repository

Weâve now set up our project, initialised renv, and created a run.R script that automates our data cleaning and analysis.

In this section, weâll initialise a Git repository and âcommitâ the current state of our files. Git will allow us to track changes to our files over time and restore previous versions.

  1. Click âCreate Repositoryâ.

  4. Click Commit to main.

8 Connect our local repository to GitHub.com

If you havenât already, create an account on GitHub.com.

  • Terminal
  • GitHub Desktop

On GitHub.com, create a new (empty) repository.

Then, in the terminal:

1git remote add origin git@github.com:username/repo.git
2git push origin main
1
Set the remote to point to the new repository on Github. You will need to replace the URL with the corresponding URL for your repository.
2
âPushâ the local history to GitHub.

  1. On GitHub.com, create a new (empty) repository.

  2. In GitHub Desktop, go to Repository â Repository Settingsâ¦

  3. Under Remote, click Add and enter:

    • Name: origin
    • URL: git@github.com:username/repo.git (Replace with the URL of your new repository)

  4. Click Save.

  5. Back in the main window, click Push origin (top bar) to upload your commits to GitHub.
